## Phase B — Issue Lifecycle

Two workflow tiers — auto-detected by `/start-issue` from the `[CATEGORY]` prefix in the issue title.

### Dev Workflow
**Categories:** `[FEAT]`, `[BUG]`, `[ENH]`, `[REFAC]`, `[PERF]`, `[SEC]`, `[UI]`, `[UX]`

```
/create-issue        → Todo
/start-issue 123     → Dev Started (branch, plan, doc, comment)
  [development on feature branch]
/ready-for-testing 123 → Automated Tests (targeted: only relevant suites)
                       → Ready for testing (merge to develop, test protocol) → STOP
/start-testing 123   → Being tested (manual or desktop E2E)
/approve-testing 123 → Ready for Prod → STOP
/deploy-issue 123    → Done (docs, full test suite, merge to main, release, close)
```

### Lightweight Workflow
**Categories:** `[INFRA]`, `[DOCS]`, `[GOV]`, `[CHORE]`

```
/create-issue        → Todo
/start-issue 123     → Dev Started (status, doc, comment — no branch)
  [do the work]
/close-issue 123     → Done (cleanup, close)
```

**GitHub Project:** {{GITHUB_PROJECT_URL}}

## Project Kickoff Protocol (Phase B)

When the user describes new features for an existing project, follow these steps **before writing any code:**

- **Create ALL issues first.** Break the plan into issues and create every one using the `/create-issue` workflow. Each issue is assigned to **Backlog** on creation.
<!-- NOTION_START -->
- **Notion setup.** If `NOTION_DATABASE_ID` is `SETUP_PENDING`, run `/setup-notion` before starting any issue.
<!-- NOTION_END -->
- **Start Sprint 1.** When running the first `/start-issue`, move all planned issues from Backlog to **Sprint 1**.
- **Then implement.** Only begin coding after all issues exist in GitHub and the sprint is set up.

**This protocol is mandatory.** It applies to the initial project plan — the first time the user describes the whole project. Never start implementing without creating all GitHub issues first.

